All autistic people deserve the support they need to thrive, whatever that means for them. Functioning labels have never achieved that. Changing the label won’t either

Support needs aren’t static. I’m autistic and my support needs change daily based on the environment, the demands put on me that day and a myriad of other factors. We can’t assess support need as a static measure on the day of diagnosis

Just as “high functioning” is lazily applied to autistic people who can mask, “profound” autism will be lazily applied to non verbal autistic people with the assumption that non verbal means unable to think independently or communicate.

If an autistic person has comorbid learning difficulties, they aren’t “profoundly” autistic. They are autistic with comorbid learning difficulties. Why do we need to subcategorise autism in order to give people the support they need?

People much more knowledgeable than I am are speaking on this, but for the record, I’m against the move to create a new category of “profound autism”. This will be used to deny the agency of those labelled with it, while denying the support needs of “high functioning” autistics

I want to get back to seeing food as food, not as smart point numbers. I want to go for walks because I enjoy walking, not to earn fit points. I don’t know what size I’m going to be this time next year, but I’m hoping whatever size I am, I’ll finally be happy and confident

This definitely made me lose weight, but don’t believe any of the claims about “wellness”. I was far from well. I’m still not happy with my body, and I still look at photos of me my skinniest and wish I could be back there, but at what cost?

Recently I tracked some of my typical weight watchers days into a calorie tracker. It came to around 900 to 1000 calories a day. I ate 0% fat yoghurt instead of the far healthier full fat version. I limited avocados. Half an avocado is the same points as a Cadbury fudge bar

I tracked every morsel that passed my lips for two straight years. I can tell you the smart point value of most foods by memory. I turned down social invitations if they involved food and would take me over my point allowance. That isn’t healthy

When lockdown hit, like a lot of people I turned to food for comfort. I’ve always had issues with binge eating, and I thought weight watchers had fixed these. It hadn’t. I look back now and realise I had replaced one disordered eating behaviour with another

CW diet culture/weight

So it’s time to confess, I’ve been a weight watchers member for the last two years. I put on a lot of weight in uni and I hated myself, so I signed up and lost 4 stone. Spoiler alert, I am no longer 4 stone lighter
